### Instruction:
in a javascript web app, how do you save text to a local file

### Response:

To save text in a local file using JavaScript, you can use the `fs` module which is built-in for Node.js. Here's an example code snippet that demonstrates how to write some data into a file called "data.txt" located on your computer's hard drive:
```javascript
const fs = require('fs');

// Write text to the file
fs.writeFile("data.txt", "This is my sample text.", (err) => {
  if(err){
    console.log(`Error writing data to file: ${err}`);
  } else{
    console.log('Data written successfully!');
  }
});
```
In this example, the `fs` module is used with its `writeFile()` method which takes three arguments - a string that represents the contents of the text you want to write in your file, the name and path of the file you wish to create or overwrite (in this case "data.txt"), and an optional callback function that will be called if there are any errors while writing data to the file.

If everything goes well, it should print out a message saying 'Data written successfully!'.
